# [Phase 1.5] Implement content hash computation

## Problem Statement
Implement SHA-256 content hashing for conflict detection. The hash includes only user-editable fields that would cause conflicts, not derived metadata.

## Why Content Hash
- **Fast duplicate detection**: Server can skip processing if hash matches
- **Conflict detection**: Different hash = different content = potential conflict
- **Bandwidth optimization**: Don't sync unchanged notes

## Hash Specification (from GH Issue #54)

### Fields INCLUDED in hash
- `title` - User-editable title
- `tags` - User-defined tags array
- `content` - Full EditorContent (Lexical JSON)
- `type` - Note type discriminator
- `daily` - For DailyNote variant
- `meeting` - For MeetingNote variant

### Fields EXCLUDED from hash
- `id` - Identifier, not content
- `createdAt` / `updatedAt` - Timestamps
- `metadata` - Derived from content by engine
- `sync` - Sync-specific metadata

## Implementation

```typescript
// packages/engine-sync/src/content-hash.ts

import { createHash } from 'node:crypto';
import type { Note, DailyNote, MeetingNote } from '@scribe/shared';

/** Hash length in hex characters (truncated from 64) */
const HASH_LENGTH = 16;

/**
 * Compute content hash for conflict detection.
 * 
 * The hash includes only user-editable content fields:
 * - title, tags, content (always)
 * - type (for discriminated union)
 * - daily/meeting (for type-specific variants)
 * 
 * Excludes: id, timestamps, metadata (derived), sync (sync-specific)
 * 
 * @param note The note to hash
 * @returns 16-character hex hash string
 */
export function computeContentHash(note: Note): string {
  // Build hash input with only conflict-relevant fields
  const hashInput: Record<string, unknown> = {
    title: note.title,
    tags: note.tags,
    content: note.content,
  };

  // Include type discriminator if present
  if (note.type) {
    hashInput.type = note.type;
  }

  // Include type-specific data
  if (isDailyNote(note)) {
    hashInput.daily = note.daily;
  }
  if (isMeetingNote(note)) {
    hashInput.meeting = note.meeting;
  }

  // Serialize and hash
  const serialized = JSON.stringify(hashInput, Object.keys(hashInput).sort());
  const hash = createHash('sha256').update(serialized).digest('hex');

  // Truncate to 16 characters (64 bits of collision resistance)
  return hash.slice(0, HASH_LENGTH);
}

// Type guards (could import from @scribe/shared)
function isDailyNote(note: Note): note is DailyNote {
  return note.type === 'daily';
}

function isMeetingNote(note: Note): note is MeetingNote {
  return note.type === 'meeting';
}
```

## Why Truncate to 16 Characters
- 16 hex chars = 64 bits = ~10^19 possible values
- Birthday paradox: collision probability < 0.1% with 1 billion notes
- Shorter hashes are easier to log and debug
- Full 64-char hash provides no practical benefit for this use case

## Determinism Considerations
- **Key sorting**: `Object.keys().sort()` ensures consistent key order
- **JSON.stringify**: Deterministic for the same input structure
- **No floating point**: Timestamps excluded, no precision issues

## Test Cases
```typescript
describe('computeContentHash', () => {
  it('returns same hash for same content', () => {
    const note = createTestNote({ title: 'Test', tags: ['a', 'b'] });
    expect(computeContentHash(note)).toBe(computeContentHash(note));
  });

  it('returns different hash for different title', () => {
    const note1 = createTestNote({ title: 'A' });
    const note2 = createTestNote({ title: 'B' });
    expect(computeContentHash(note1)).not.toBe(computeContentHash(note2));
  });

  it('ignores updatedAt timestamp changes', () => {
    const note1 = createTestNote({ updatedAt: 1000 });
    const note2 = { ...note1, updatedAt: 2000 };
    expect(computeContentHash(note1)).toBe(computeContentHash(note2));
  });

  it('ignores sync metadata changes', () => {
    const note1 = createTestNote({});
    const note2 = { ...note1, sync: { version: 5, contentHash: 'x' } };
    expect(computeContentHash(note1)).toBe(computeContentHash(note2));
  });

